CMV infection

Source

  • Cytomegalo virus = human herpevirus 5. (CMV)
  • ds-DNA genome
  • CMV virus infection is asymptomatic in healthy individuals but can cause life threatening organ dysfunction in immunocompromised patients.
  • After infection, CMV virus becomes latent but can reactivate at any time. Infection is controlled by cytotoxic T cell immunity.
    • CMV affects salivary glands and infection can lead to mucoepidermoid carcinoma. (the commonest malignant salivary gland tumor). Source
  • CMV is extremely common; by 6 years of age 60% of the population is exposed.
    • 70% of adults in developed countries and 100% of adults in developing countries are infected.
  • Presentation:
    • Immunocompetent hosts: Asymptomatic or mononucleosis.
    • However, unlike EBV mononculeosis, there is no pharyngeal exudate and no heterophile antibodies in CMV infection.
    • In immunosuppressed hosts, (HIV, organ transplant, bone marrow transplant), CMV can cause hepatitis, pneumonitis and colitis.
    • Treatment: gangiclovir, valcanciclovir etc. (valganciclovir is the oral prodrug).
      • Ganciclovir becomes activated in viral infected cells and inhibits viral DNA polymerases.
  • normal serum osmolality should range from 275 to 295 mOsm/kg

  • Acetyl CoA can have 3 fates:
    1. Enters krebs cycle --> produces ATP
    2. Exported back to cytoplasm to make fatty acids.
    3. Enters ketogenic pathway to from acetoacetic acid.
  • In low insulin, high glucagon states, Acetyl CoA entry into Krebs cycle is rate limiting. Therefore, more of it ends up in the ketogenic pathway. => ketosis!
  • Insulin deficiency (absolute or relative - i.e insufficient to overcome counterregulatory hormones like cortisol / catecholamines in time of stress)
  • Insulin deficiency is more severe in DKA
  • DKA (rather than HHS)is more commonly the presenting condition of new onset DM.
  • HHS usually occurs with prexisting disease.
  • DKA : new onset DM, infection
  • HHS: Inadequate insulin administration, infection.
  • Any acute stressor (MI, stroke) (? increase catecholamine and cortisol acvitity) can precipitate DKA / HHS

Deficits in DKA and HSS of water and electrolytes

  • If SBP < 90 - 500 ml bolus within 15 minutes, and repeat. Usually 500 - 1000 ml is required.
    • Second liter of fluid usually requires potassium addition. See [[#Electrolytes]] below.
    • rise of HCO3 of 3mmol/L/hr. (mnemonic: the 3 in HCO3 -> 3mmol / hr rise)
  • If blood glucose falls below 14mmol/L (252 mg/Ld) add 10% dextrose 125 ml/hr.
    • Note "Add" not "replace"
  • Patients have a total potassium deficit (due to vomiting and diuresis) but it is masked by shift of KCl from ICF to ECF. Insulin administration will unmask the deficit and cause rapid fall of serum K+ as K+ shifts back into cells.

Uraemic encephalopathy

Source

  • Is a clinical diagnosis. There are no specific imaging or other diagnosis findings.
  • Proposed mechanism: various metabolites accumulate and cause suppression of GABA receptors and stimulation of glutamate (NMDA) receptors.
  • Symptom severity depends on chronicity of symptoms.
    • Chronic - due to slow decline of GFR
      • Gradual decline in mental functions. Restlessness, cognitive impairment, drowsiness, inability to concentrate.
      • Because it's slow, psychometric testing is required to identify the decline.
    • Acute - due to acute drop in GFR.
      • Confusion, disorientation, delirium, seizures, coma.
      • Physical findings: hyperreflexia, asterexis, papilloedema, nystagmus +/- neuropathy and myopathy.
  • Treatment:
    • Uraemic encephalopathy is an absolute indication of renal replacement therapy.

Other features of uraemia

  • Uraemic frost
  • Mild icterus
  • Oral signs : gingival hyperplasia and bleeding, enamel hypoplasia
  • Pericardial rub
  • pulmonary oedema
  • peripheral oedema
  • Severe hypertension
